+## 3. Harmonic Far-Field Comparison
+
+### 3.1 Ordinary NS / Vasseur split
+
+In ordinary NS:
+
+- one has the local Poisson pressure law,
+- one can split pressure into near and far pieces on a local ball/cylinder,
+- the far part is harmonic on the local region because its source is outside.
+
+This is the structural basis of the loophole.
+
+### 3.2 Why Tao's averaging changes the picture
+
+Rotations and dilations alone would preserve the harmonic character of a locally harmonic function under geometric pullback. But Tao's averaging also uses **order-zero Fourier multipliers** on the inputs and output.
+
+- [CHECKED] Those multipliers are nonlocal.
+- [CHECKED] Nonlocal multipliers do not preserve **local** harmonicity in the sense the loophole needs, because they mix values from outside the local region back into the region.
+- [CHECKED] Thus even if one decomposed each inner NS term into near/far pressure pieces before averaging, the averaged output would no longer be a clean harmonic far-field component on the working cylinder.
+
+### 3.3 Consequence for the loophole
+
+The loophole requires:
+
+1. a scalar pressure obeying a local Poisson law,
+2. a near/far split,
+3. a far piece harmonic on `Q_k`,
+4. Harnack/oscillation control of that harmonic piece.
+
+Tao's averaged construction keeps only the high-level cancellation and harmonic-analysis estimates. It does **not** preserve this local elliptic decomposition in a usable form.
+
+## 4. Bottleneck Replacement Analysis
+
+### 4.1 Old bottleneck
+
+Ordinary Vasseur bottleneck:
+
+```text
+I_k ≤ ||P_{k21}||_{L^q} ||d_k||_{L^2} ||1_{v_k>0}||_{L^{2q/(q-2)}}
+    ≤ C_q C^k U_{k-1}^{4/3 - 5/(3q)}.
